// LA-30 doc 5 §2 C2 (failure routing) — the design's canonical repro.
// Nothing ever resolves `p`; a timer callback throws, uncaught.
//
// Pre-LA-30 pump (gone; LANG_PUMP=1 reproduces it until M6): the throw broke
// the pump loop `await p` was running and unwound into this file's unrelated
// `catch` — an exception teleported into a handler that had nothing to do
// with the timer (doc 5 §2: "spooky"). Under the pump this file prints the
// MISROUTED line and exits 0 — the recorded pre-flip divergence.
//
// Tasks (asserted): the callback is its own task, so its throw is
// program-uncaught (standard banner, exit 1 — the exit-codes contract) and
// is NEVER delivered to the unrelated `await p`. The catch prints only on a
// misroute, deliberately: what the parked await itself observes during
// shutdown is engine-incidental (the interpreters stash the uncaught throw
// and drain task 0 first, so its await throws C3's drain error into this
// catch; LLVM's doc-2 §8 throw gate exits with task 0 still parked, so the
// catch never runs) — G13 says assert the contract, never the incidental
// ordering. C3's drain-throw behavior is asserted by its own two files.
// Byte-identical on oracle/IR/LLVM.
Promise<int> p = Promise();                   // nothing ever resolves p
std::sysTimerStart(5, 0, (n) => { throw RuntimeException("boom"); });
try { int x = await p; } catch (IException e) {
    // C2's whole point: the timer's boom must never land here.
    if (e.message == "boom") console.writeln("MISROUTED: caught the timer's throw");
}
